A note on a new existence result for reflected BSDEs with interconnected obstacles

Tiziano De Angelis and Giorgio Ferrari and Saïd Hamadène T. De Angelis: School of Mathematics, University of Leeds, Woodhouse Lane, LS2 9JT Leeds, UK. t.deangelis@leeds.ac.uk G. Ferrari: Center for Mathematical Economics, Bielefeld University, Universitätsstrasse 25, 33615, Bielefeld, Germany. giorgio.ferrari@uni-bielefeld.de S. Hamadène: Le Mans Université, LMM, Avenue Olivier Messiaen, 72085 Le Mans, Cedex 9, France. hamadene@univ-lemans.fr
Abstract.

In this note we prove existence of a solution to a system of Markovian BSDEs with interconnected obstacles. A key feature of our system, and the main novelty of this paper, is that we allow for the driver fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} of the i𝑖i-th component of the Y𝑌Y-process to depend on all components of the Z𝑍Z-process. This extends the existing theory on reflected BSDEs, which only addresses problems where fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} depends on Zisuperscript𝑍𝑖Z^{i}.

If for i=1,…,m𝑖1…𝑚i=1,...,m, fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} does not depend on (yi)i=1,msubscriptsuperscript𝑦𝑖𝑖1𝑚(y^{i})_{i=1,m} and (zi)i=1,msubscriptsuperscript𝑧𝑖𝑖1𝑚(z^{i})_{i=1,m}, the solution of (1.1) is linked to an optimal switching problem. The latter is a problem in which a decision maker (or controller) controls a (stochastic) system which may operate in different modes (e.g., a power plant). The aim of the controller is to maximise some performance criterion by optimally choosing controls of the form δ:=(τn,ζn)n≥0assign𝛿subscriptsubscript𝜏𝑛subscript𝜁𝑛𝑛0\delta:=(\tau_{n},\zeta_{n})_{n\geq 0}. Here (τn)n≥0subscriptsubscript𝜏𝑛𝑛0(\tau_{n})_{n\geq 0} denotes an increasing sequence of (stopping) times at which the controller switches the system across different operating modes. Moreover, (ζn)n≥0subscriptsubscript𝜁𝑛𝑛0(\zeta_{n})_{n\geq 0} is a sequence of random variables taking their values in {1,…,m}1…𝑚\{1,...,m\}. Each ζnsubscript𝜁𝑛\zeta_{n} represents the system’s new operating mode after a switch has occurred at time τnsubscript𝜏𝑛\tau_{n}.

It is also known that the solution of (1.1) enables to construct an optimal strategy as well.

It is important to remark that a characterization as in (1.2) also holds in non-Markovian frameworks and we mention that switching problems often arise in economics, finance and power system management, amongst many other applied fields (see e.g. [2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 8, 10, 18, 19, 21, 22] and the references therein).

Problems like (1.1) have been studied at a theoretical level in the case when, for any i=1,…,m𝑖1…𝑚i=1,...,m, the function fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} depends only on the state variable zisuperscript𝑧𝑖z^{i} and possibly on (yi)i∈Γsubscriptsuperscript𝑦𝑖𝑖Γ(y^{i})_{i\in\Gamma} (see, e.g., [6, 13]). In that setting existence (and uniqueness) results were provided (also for the non-Markovian case) by using comparison principles for solutions of BSDEs. Such comparisons do not hold in our framework since fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} depends on (zi)i∈Γsubscriptsuperscript𝑧𝑖𝑖Γ(z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma}, hence we must rely on different methods.

The main objective of this paper is indeed to consider systems in which, for i=1,…,m𝑖1…𝑚i=1,...,m, functions fisubscript𝑓𝑖f_{i} not only depend on the state variable zi∈ℝdsuperscript𝑧𝑖superscriptℝ𝑑z^{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d} but on all components of the state variable z:=(zi)i∈Γassign𝑧subscriptsuperscript𝑧𝑖𝑖Γz:=(z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma}. In particular we show that if σ​σ⊤𝜎superscript𝜎top\sigma\sigma^{\top} is bounded and uniformly elliptic, then (1.1) has a solution, provided that the switching costs (gi​j)i,j∈Γsubscriptsubscript𝑔𝑖𝑗𝑖𝑗Γ(g_{ij})_{i,j\in\Gamma} are sufficiently regular. We adopt a usual penalization scheme (see (3.5) below) to handle the reflection constraints and rely deeply on essentially three facts: i) the representation of solutions of BSDEs as deterministic functions of t𝑡t and X𝑋X; ii) smoothness of gi​jsubscript𝑔𝑖𝑗g_{ij}, which enables fundamental bounds in the penalisation scheme; iii) existence of a transition density of Xst,xsubscriptsuperscript𝑋𝑡𝑥𝑠X^{t,x}_{s} for any s>t𝑠𝑡s>t, which satisfies a so-called domination condition.

Our work is a first step towards the solution of (1.1) in general non-Markovian setup. The paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we set out the notations and make standing assumptions that hold throughout the paper. In Section 3, we prove our existence result in a number of steps. First we introduce the penalization scheme associated with (1.1) and study its properties (in particular we show in Proposition 3.1 that the time derivative of the penalizing term is uniformly bounded). Then we use an argument based on weak convergence and the aforementioned domination condition (see also [12]) to obtain a convergent subsequence of solutions to the penalized problems. We finally show that the limit of such subsequence solves (1.1) and provide a representation of (Yi,Zi)i∈Γsubscriptsuperscript𝑌𝑖superscript𝑍𝑖𝑖Γ(Y^{i},Z^{i})_{i\in\Gamma} as deterministic functions of (t,X)𝑡𝑋(t,X). We leave for future investigation questions of uniqueness of the solution and its links to optimal switching problems. The latter will inevitably feature a more general structure than (1.2).
